    "body": "### Problem\n\nwhat happens when '\\*' or '#' is typed varies slightly based on the mode.\nin normal-mode it searches for the **'word'** under the cursor.\nin visual-mode it searches for the **selected text**.\nbut when used in mappings, no matter which mode you are in, the normal-mode version is invoked. (even when using feedkeys)\nI tested this in Nvim v0.8.0 when the search by selection feature was added, and the issue is also there.\nyou can hack your way around this by copying the lua function used internally into your own config: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/master/runtime/lua/vim/_defaults.lua#L49\nbut this is less than ideal for obvious reasons.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. nvim --clean\n2. :vnoremap * *\n3. type \"foo bar foo bar\" then enter visual-mode and select \"foo bar\" then type '*' or '#'\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nexit visual-mode, highlight \"foo bar\" and jump to next/previous occurrences. instead it just highlights the vim-word \"bar\" then jumps while still in visual-mode.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.12.0-dev-e084a990\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\ntechnically yes, but vim doesn't have the feature to search for selected text anyway.\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nDebian 13 (trixie) \n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nsuckless-terminal v0.9.2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nscreen-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nbuilt from source by following BUILD.md",
